—actually makes more palpable collective memory’s limitations and the opacity of the historical past, which always lies beyond the reach of living memory. Thwarting skepticism, however, he eventually looks to literature—specifically writers such as Marcel Proust, Walter Scott, and W. G. Sebald—to uncover subtle nuances of temporality that might offer inconspicuous emblems of a past historical reality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCollective memoryxPhilosophy. 0aCollective memory. 0aMemoryxSocial aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aMarcel Proust.  aWalter Scott.  acollective memory.  ahabitus.  ahistorical skepticism.  ahistorical time.  amass media.  asymbolic configuration.  avisual arts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022639915740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226399294423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226399294/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles